[Black "Road To The Main Line #15"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6
{ Bg7 is of course playable but then Black can't play the 'Gurgenidze System' in the Maroczy Bind which is part of this repertoire. }
5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Bc4 O-O 8. O-O
{ The main line is 8. Bb3  (see next chapter)  while 8. f3 is covered under the 7. f3 move order while 8. Qd2 would be met by Ng4 so White gives up on castling queenside. }
8... Nxe4
{ d6 would tranpose to traditional Dragon where White's setup isn't too challanging but the Nxe4 trick is even better ! }
9. Nxe4 d5 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Bd3 dxe4 12. Bxe4
{ On the first sight it looks as White has the better pawn structure but in fact the activity of the pieces and possibility to attack weaknesses is what defines this position. }
12... Qc7 { Ba6 is also fine but I prefer keeping Queens on the board. } 13. c3
Rb8 14. Qe2 Be6
{ Objectively the position is equal but I slightly prefer Black who can at some point prepare the advance of the central pawns ...f5 and ...e5 while the damaged pawn structure on the queenside is not felt as Black has a lot of activity along the b-file. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Road To The Main Line"]
[Black "Road To The Main Line #16"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6
{ 4... Bg7 is of course playable but then Black can't play the 'Gurgenidze System' in the Maroczy Bind which is part of this repertoire. }
5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Nb3 { This doesn't look too ambitious. } 6... Nf6
{ 6... Bxc3 is a very interesting alternative, but let's stick to the simple plan. }
7. g4
{ There's an idea to play ...g5 with colors reversed in the English Opening thus indeed it should be considered but I don't think it's any good for White. }
7... d6 8. g5 Nh5
{ 8... Nd7 must be OK but after h4 White's play is simple. Meanwhile this approach stops White's attack completely. It may seem he can break on the kingside and even win a pawn but it will take time and also he will be forced to give up his light squared Bishop without which I just don't believe Black can be in any troubles. }
9. Be2 O-O
{ A Novelty. At this point some other moves could be considered but I like castle and we can also get into this position via 7. Be2 O-O 8. g4 move order. }
10. Bxh5 gxh5 11. Nd5
{ 11. Qxh5 is not impressive as Black doesn't care about that pawn anyway and after 11... a5 with some ...Nb4 Black is better. It's advised for White to consolidate first and argue that h5 will fall later. }
11... a5 12. a4 Nb4 13. Ne3 Be6
{ Black is the first one to attack anyway and with White's King still in the middle and Black's great Bishops dominating the board I just dislike White's chances. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Main Line"]
[Black "The Main Line #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6
{ Bg7 is of course playable but then Black can't play 'Gurgenidze System' in the Maroczy Bind which is part of this repertoire. }
5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Bc4 O-O 8. Bb3
{ The Main Line and only way for White to fight for the initiative. } 8... d6
9. h3
{ This move shows no interest in the kingside attack with h4. White is going to play in positional manner and I think we can easily overtake the initiative. }
9... Na5
{ There's nothing wrong with the most popular Bd7 but I think the text is more ambitious. }
10. O-O b6 11. Re1 Bb7 12. Bg5 h6
{ I can't understand why 12.. .Nxb3 is most popular. Of course Black is happy to get Bishop pair but I don't see any reason to hurry with this exchange. }
13. Bh4 { 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Bd5 Rc8 is just nothing to fear. } 13... Qd7
{ My Novelty and I am amazed no one has played it before me. The idea is to keep things flexible and Rc8 is met by 14. Nd5 ! while here that's not working. I advice you to check that with the engine to get better feeling for the position. }
14. Qd2 Rac8
{ Nxb3 15. axb3 Nh5 would transpose to famous game V.Anand - G.Kasparov, Linares 2003 which was fine for Black but I like ...Rac8 even more as we are going to exchange White's Bishop on b3 without improving White's structure. }
15. f3
{ 15. Nf3 g5 16. Bg3 Nc4 was already clearly better for Black in D.Cerovic - P.Nguyen, Graz 2018. }
15... Nc4 16. Bxc4 Rxc4 17. Bf2 Rfc8 18. a4 a6
{ The position is equal although Black's play looks much easier to me. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Main Line"]
[Black "The Main Line #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6
{ Bg7 is of course playable but then Black can't play 'Gurgenidze System' in the Maroczy Bind which is part of this repertoire. }
5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Bc4 O-O 8. Bb3
{ The Main Line and only way for White to fight for the initiative. } 8... d6
9. f3 Bd7 10. h4
{ Apart from 10. Qd2 Negi wrote whole additional chapter on 10. h4. I believe it is the most dangerous line as White goes straight into the action and can play Qd2 only later. }
10... Nxd4 11. Bxd4 b5 12. h5 { 12. Qd2 just transposes to 10. Qd2. } 12... e6
{ I couldn't find any advantage for White in this line. a5 is also playable but there is one slightly inferior endgame I didn't want to recommend. }
13. hxg6 hxg6 14. a4 bxa4 15. Nxa4 Qa5+
{ Disrupting White's setup. A Novelty instead of dubious Bc6 which was played in A.Romero Holmes - G.Rechlis, Groningen 1985. }
16. Kf2
{ It seems White should move the King because   16.Nc3  Qb4  or   16.Bc3  Qg5  look really nice for Black. Now White may have some Nc5 as a threat. }
16... Rfb8 { I believe the position is double edged. } 17. Qd3
{ It is important to note 17. Nc5 is not winning because of accurate Qb4 ! }
17... Qc7
{ returning to a safe square and Black prepares equalizing ...d5 or some ...a5 with ...Rb4. }
*

