{ The Main Line and only way for White to fight for the initiative. } 8... d6
9. f3 Bd7 10. h4
{ Apart from 10. Qd2 Negi wrote whole additional chapter on 10. h4. I believe it is the most dangerous line as White goes straight into the action and can play Qd2 only later. }
10... Nxd4 11. Bxd4 b5 12. h5 { 12. Qd2 just transposes to 10. Qd2. } 12... e6
{ I couldn't find any advantage for White in this line. a5 is also playable but there is one slightly inferior endgame I didn't want to recommend. }
13. hxg6 hxg6 14. Qd2 b4 { a5 15. a4 is indeed great for White. } 15. Ne2 a5
16. Be3
{ No one has tried it in OTB game but Bh6 idea is very common and Black needs to be ready against it. I think that's critical test for this entire variation I recommend starting with e6. }
16... a4 17. Bc4 Qc7 18. Bh6 Nxe4
{ Ng4 might be engine's choice but if you analyse further you will understand Black is unfortunately lost there. }
19. Bxg7 Kxg7 20. Qh6+ Kf6 21. Qf4+ Kg7 22. Qxe4
{ White could make a draw with 22. Qh6 but let's analyse if he can get more than a draw. }
22... d5 { Regaining a piece. } 23. Bxd5
{ If 13. Qd4+ e5 14. Qxd5 then ... Be6. } 23... exd5 24. Qd4+ f6 25. Qe3 Qe5
26. Qh6+ { The only possible ambitious try. } 26... Kf7 27. Qh7+ Ke6 28. O-O-O
Rh8 29. Nd4+ Kd6 30. Qxh8 Rxh8 31. Rxh8 Qg5+ 32. Rd2 Qe3
{ and the position is just equal but both players can play on. This is the longest line in the repertoire but important one to prove the entire variation is valid. }
