[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Main Line"]
[Black "The Main Line #15"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6
{ Bg7 is of course playable but then Black can't play 'Gurgenidze System' in the Maroczy Bind which is part of this repertoire. }
5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Bc4 O-O 8. Bb3
{ The Main Line and only way for White to fight for the initiative. } 8... d6
9. h3
{ This move shows no interest in the kingside attack with h4. White is going to play in positional manner and I think we can easily overtake the initiative. }
9... Na5
{ There's nothing wrong with the most popular Bd7 but I think the text is more ambitious. }
10. O-O b6 11. Re1 Bb7 12. Bg5 h6
{ I can't understand why 12.. .Nxb3 is most popular. Of course Black is happy to get Bishop pair but I don't see any reason to hurry with this exchange. }
13. Bh4 { 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Bd5 Rc8 is just nothing to fear. } 13... Qd7 14.
Nd5
{ As mentioned a move earlier, this would be strong after 13...Rc8 but here it doesn't work tactically. }
14... Nxb3 15. axb3
{ With the Rook on c8 rather the Queen on d7 15.Bxf6 would also be an option. Here it just looses to simple ...Nxa1. }
15... Nxd5 16. exd5 g5
{ and that's the big point of 13...Qd7 that such moves are possible! With the Rook on c8 rather the Queen on d7 White would have Nf5 with a deadly attack. }
17. Bg3 Bxd5 18. Qd3 e6
{ Bishop pair and extra pawn should give decisive advantage but White has some compensation thanks to active pieces. All in all Black is clearly better and White must be careful not to loose quickly. }
