[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Maroczy Bind - Gurgenidze System"]
[Black "Maroczy Bind - Gurgenidze System #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6
{ Bg7 is of course playable but then Black can't play 'Gurgenidze System' in the Maroczy Bind which is part of this repertoire. }
5. c4
{ Entering so called Maroczy Bind setup which isn't possible in traditional Dragon but we have to learn it. This is the price we pay for choosing this move order. }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3 d6 7. f3
{ This is tricky line where White delays Be2 and protects e4 so he can get Nd5 quickly and keep the King in the centre should he manage to exchange Queens. }
7... Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Bg7 9. Be3 O-O 10. Qd2 { and now we should stick to our gun }
10... a5 11. b3 { 11. Be2 a4 transposes to our main line } 11... Be6
{ a4 would be met by 12. b4 ! and White had some small advantage in M.Carlsen-F. Caruana, St Louis 2014. }
12. Be2 Nd7 13. O-O Nc5
{ now we reached position similar to the old main line in the Maroczy where the Bishop is on c6 rather than e6. In that line Black forces White to play f2-f3, here White has already commited himself to playing f2-f3 so maybe the Bishop on e6 is just a little bit more useful. }
14. Rab1 Qb6 15. Rfc1 Rfc8 16. Kh1 Qb4
{ with complex game ahead in L.Van Wely - E. Iturrizaga, Istanbul 2012 } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Maroczy Bind - Gurgenidze System"]
[Black " Maroczy Bind - Gurgenidze System #3 - 11. Na4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6
{ 4... Bg7 is of course playable but then Black can't play 'Gurgenidze System' in the Maroczy Bind which is part of this repertoire. }
5. c4
{ Entering so called Maroczy Bind setup which isn't possible in traditional Dragon but we have to learn it. This is the price we pay for choosing this move order. }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3 d6 7. f3
{ This is tricky line where White delays Be2 and protects e4 so he can get Nd5 quickly and keep the King in the centre should he manage to exchange Queens. }
7... Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Bg7 9. Be3 O-O 10. Qd2 { and now we should stick to our gun }
10... a5 11. Na4
{ An extremely rare move at a time when this course was prepared but some months later it was recommended by John Shaw in 'Playing 1. e4' which ensures a huge rise in popularity. The idea is simple but not common in the Maroczy. White wants to block the queenside, castle there and storm the kingside with h4, g4 as if it was a normal Dragon. It took me some time to find an antidote. }
11... Be6
{ We must play actively even at a cost of a pawn. 11... Nd7 12. O-O-O ! would be really dangerous in my opinion. }
12. Nb6 Rb8 13. Qxa5
{ White won a pawn but he is behind in the development and that should be enough for us to maintain the balance. }
13... Nd7 14. Qb4 f5
{ With the White King still in the middle that's certainly the way to go. } 15.
Bd3 { Shaw's Novelty. } 15... Ne5 16. O-O-O
{ So White has completed the development and now it's time for Black to capitalize on the activity. }
16... fxe4
{ A Novelty which was suggested to me by my engine. Shaw considers only 16... Nxd3 where White keeps extra pawn and some advantage. I don't know why he missed it as it's all forced now. }
17. Bxe4 { 17. fxe4 is wrong in view of 17... Ng4. } 17... Nxc4 18. Nxc4 Qc8
19. Kb1 Qxc4
{ If you must keep the Queens on the board then 19... Bxc4 is playable but then objectively White is for choice. }
20. Qxc4 Bxc4 { And I believe White has no advantage here. } *

