[Black "Maroczy Bind - Gurgenidze System #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6
{ Bg7 is of course playable but then Black can't play 'Gurgenidze System' in the Maroczy Bind which is part of this repertoire. }
5. c4
{ Entering so called Maroczy Bind setup which isn't possible in traditional Dragon but we have to learn it. This is the price we pay for choosing this move order. }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3 d6 7. Be2 { Of course 7. Be3 would be innacurate due to Ng4. }
7... Nxd4 { Black is happy to exchange some pieces as he has less space. } 8.
Qxd4 Bg7 9. Bg5 O-O 10. Qe3 Be6 11. O-O Qb6
{ very nice resource as pointed out by Greet. Black is happy to exchange Queens and is not afraid to damage the structure due to dynamic possibilities. }
12. Qd2 Qa5 { a5 could be considered } 13. Rac1 Rfc8 14. b3 a6
{ so we went for a bit different line this time but those positions are dangerous for Black only when White's King is still on e1 and he has already played f3 so he could go Na4 forcing slightly favourable endgame. }
15. f3 b5 { Here Black obtains great counterplay. } *

