[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Maroczy Bind - Gurgenidze System"]
[Black " Maroczy Bind - Gurgenidze System #15 - 12. Kf2!?"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6
{ 4... Bg7 is of course playable but then Black can't play 'Gurgenidze System' in the Maroczy Bind which is part of this repertoire. }
5. c4
{ Entering so called Maroczy Bind setup which isn't possible in traditional Dragon but we have to learn it. This is the price we pay for choosing this move order. }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3 d6 7. Be2
{ Of course 7. Be3 would be innacurate due to 7... Ng4. } 7... Nxd4
{ Black is happy to exchange some pieces as he has less space. } 8. Qxd4 Bg7 9.
Be3 O-O 10. Qd2 a5
{ 10... Be6 with ...Qa5 is the main line but I believe the line I recommend here is easier to learn and it is by no means worse in my opinion. }
11. f3 a4 12. Kf2
{ A tricky fresh move. The idea is to protect the Bishop on e2, I know it may sound too abstract but if you look at the lines where White castles instead you will quickly get the point. Also the King is just better placed here than on g1 in case of Queen's exchange. }
12... Be6
{ 12... Qa5 is not a mistake and that's how I reacted when I met this line for the first time. However now I believe it's less accurate as it is not clear if we want to exchange Queens now. Also a typical drawback of putting the Bishop to e6 early is f4-f5 but that's not a plan here with the King on f2. }
13. Rac1 Nd7 14. Nd5 Nc5
{ I tried to analyse a Novelty 14... f5 which is really messy. You can investigate in on your own and play it if you really need to complicate the game. }
15. Rhd1 Re8
{ A new move, Black can consider ...Qa5 next but he can wait, also ...Bxd5 can be a move sometimes depending on how White continues. I like this flexible option much more than passive 15... b6 which is correspondence players' choice. To be honest White has a plus here but it's not the end of the world. }
*

