{ Be6 is possible but after 12.O-O a4 13. f4 ! as played for the first time in Z.Almasi - B.Macieja, Khanty-Mansiysk 2010 Black's Bishop feels uncomfortable on e6 and I believe White is slightly better. Still, you can play this way if you are playing for a win and want to keep things more complicated. }
12. c5 { This is the point of 11. Rd1 } 12... Be6 13. cxd6 Qxd6 14. Qxd6 exd6
15. a3 Rfd8
{ On a first sight Black's position looks worse as the pawn on d6 is weak but as we will see Black has better piece play. At the moment ... Bb3 followed by ...d5 is an idea. }
16. Bb6 { Disrupting Black's coordination a bit } 16... Rdc8
{ Rd7 17.O-O Bb3 18. Rd2 Re7 was seen in M.Szelag - M.Kanarek, Katowice 2017 and Black went on to win a nice game so you can actually choose play this way as well. }
17. O-O { 17. Rxd6 Nd7 will regain a pawn with some pressure. } 17... Bc4
{ A Novelty. Rc6 was played in one correspondence game and after some complications the game ended in a draw but the line is unnatural for practical players. }
18. Rfe1 Nd7 19. Bd4 Ne5
{ Black has adequate play to compensate a weak pawn on d6. } *

