1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6
{ 4... Bg7 is of course playable but then Black can't play 'Gurgenidze System' in the Maroczy Bind which is part of this repertoire. }
5. c4
{ Entering so called Maroczy Bind setup which isn't possible in traditional Dragon but we have to learn it. This is the price we pay for choosing this move order. }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3 d6 7. Be2
{ Of course 7. Be3 would be innacurate due to 7... Ng4. } 7... Nxd4
{ Black is happy to exchange some pieces as he has less space. } 8. Qxd4 Bg7 9.
Be3 O-O 10. Qd2 a5
{ 10... Be6 with ...Qa5 is the main line but I believe the line I recommend here is easier to learn and it is by no means worse in my opinion. }
11. Rd1 a4
{ 11. ..Be6 is possible but after 12. O-O a4 13. f4 ! as played for the first time in Z. Almasi - B.Macieja, Khanty-Mansiysk 2010 Black's Bishop feels uncomfortable on e6 and I believe White is slightly better. Still, you can play this way if you are playing for a win and want to keep things more complicated. }
12. O-O
{ Originally I haven't covered it in this move order as 12. c5 seems to be the biggest challenge and in general it's better not to hurry with a castle and have the King in the center in case of Queen exchange. It turns out to be much trickier than it looks. }
12... Qa5 13. Bd4 Bd7
{ When I got this line on the board for the first time  (in a game during summer 2018)  I just played natural 13... Be6 not realizing White can go 14. f4 ! transposing to the aforementioned game Z. Almasi - B.Macieja, which I wanted to avoid. In this particular line when White kind of lost a tempo for Bd4 and keeps f2-f4 as an idea I suggest developing the Bishop to c6 when f4 would only weaken White's structure. }
14. Bxf6
{ This forced move is not dangerous but over the board it wasn't so clear to me. Certainly that's something we should have a quick look. }
14... Bxf6 15. Nd5 Kg7
{ A Novelty. Please note that 15... Qxd2 16. Rxd2 Kg7 is not the same as then White has strong 17. c5 ! Black still should be OK, the game N. Huschenbeth - I.Gaponenko, Bad Woerishofen 2011 ended in a draw but we shouldn't give White even a shadow advantage if we can. }
16. Nxf6 Qxd2 17. Nh5+
{ at least spoiling Black's structure while 17. Rxd2 Kxf6 18. c5 Bc6 is nothing. Compare it with the position reached in aforementioned game Huschenbeth-Gaponenko to fully grasp the idea. }
17... gxh5 18. Rxd2 Ra5
{ And despite a weak pawn on h5 Black has full counterplay on c4 with ...Rc8 and ... Be6 coming. }
