[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4
{ This wouldn't be possible if Black chooses Nc6 move order but then he would have to learn 3. Bb5 Rossolimo. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3
{ For couple years I was struggling to find a satisfactory way to meet this system but finally I managed to do so and I will present a nice Novelty. }
5... Nc6 6. Qa4 d6 7. e5 dxe5
{ The main move. Ng4 !? is an alternative but to my knowledge White has chances for slight edge there. }
8. Nxe5 Bg7
{ Nice pawn sacrifice. Bd7 is most popular but I don't like giving Bishop pair so easily. }
9. Bb5 O-O 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Bxc6 Rb8 12. O-O
{ Noone has tried greedy 12. Qxa7 and rightly so as after ...Qd6 13. Bf3 Ba6 he faces huge difficulties finishing the development. }
12... Qc7 13. Re1 Rb6
{ A Novelty I had a chance to use just before publishing this repertoire. This is improvement over the game A.Naiditsch - D. Hausrath, Germany 2011 which continued Bb7 14. Bxb7 Rxb7 15. Bf4 with small advantage as pointed out in Kornev's book 'Rossolimo and friends'. Meanwhile please note Ng4 as I played in H. Stevic - P.Nguyen, Zagreb 2017 was a big blunder as after 14. Bf4 e5 15. Bg3 Rxb2 16. Nd5 White was nearly winning. }
14. Bf3 Bb7 15. Bf4 { White wins a tempo but the pawn on b2 is hanging now. }
15... Qc8 16. Bxb7 Qxb7
{ with sufficient compensation. Actually most likely Black will regain material soon. My game continued }
17. Qa3 Rb4 18. Bg3 Rc8
{ All moves are natural, Black is building serious pressure. } 19. Rad1
{ This position was reached in B.Dastan - P.Nguyen, Graz 2018 } 19... Bf8
{ covering 8th rank, e7 pawn and eyeing White's Queen after possible ...e6 is what I should have played where I believe White is in serious troubles. Instead I played 19.. .h5 missing strong 20. Rxe7 ! Qxe7 21. Bd6 and after forced sequence I ended up in worse endgame which I lost to tournament's winner. }
