{ The main move. 7... Ng4 !? is an alternative but to my knowledge White has chances for slight edge there. }
8. Nxe5 Bg7
{ Nice pawn sacrifice. 8... Bd7 is most popular but I don't like giving Bishop pair so easily. }
9. Bb5 O-O 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Bxc6 Rb8 12. O-O
{ Noone has tried greedy 12. Qxa7 and rightly so as after ...Qd6 13. Bf3 Ba6 he faces huge difficulties finishing the development. }
12... Qc7 13. Re1 Rb6
{ A Novelty I had a chance to use just before publishing this repertoire. This is improvement over the game A.Naiditsch - D. Hausrath, Germany 2011 which continued 13... Bb7 14. Bxb7 Rxb7 15. Bf4 with small advantage as pointed out in Kornev's book 'Rossolimo and friends'. Meanwhile please note 13... Ng4 as I played in H. Stevic - P.Nguyen, Zagreb 2017 was a big blunder as after 14. Bf4 e5 15. Bg3 Rxb2 16. Nd5 White was nearly winning. }
14. Nd5
{ It turned out 13... Rb6 ! has been played 11 days before my game in the game T.Rendle - A.Stewart, England 2018. There White played this move which is best and I haven't covered it originally. }
14... Nxd5 15. Bxd5 Bxb2
{ If we don't take a pawn we still keep some compensation but it might not be enough so when we can take we should. }
16. Bxb2 Rxb2 17. Bb3
{ It looks our Rook is trapped but with ...Bf5 hitting c2 or ...Be6 everything is under control. }
17... Qc5 { First we stop Qa3 or Qd4. } 18. Qe4
{ If some 18. h3 then just 18... Be6. } 18... Be6
{ 18... Bf5 should equalize too. } 19. Bxe6 fxe6 20. Qxe6+
{ In the aforementioned game 20. Re2 Qd5 was played and Black drew easily against 200+ higher rated opponent. }
20... Rf7 21. Re2 Rxc2
{ Black regains a pawn and it should all end in a draw. It proves how well it holds theoretically but I understand reaching this position against lower rated player might not be what we want... That's life being Black and if you expect your lower rated opponent to go for such lines you have to take risk earlier. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Meeting Alapin"]
[Black "Meeting Alapin #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. c3 d5 4. e5
{ The only way to make move order 2. Nf3 & 3. c3 a bit independent. 4. exd5 just transposes to the lines considered after 2. c3. }
4... Nc6 5. d4 Bg4 { Putting some pressure on the d4 pawn. } 6. Bb5 Qb6 7.
Bxc6+ Qxc6
{ bxc6 is also playable but in this case paradoxically I prefer keeping pawn on the b-file. }
8. O-O Bg7 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 e6
{ With full equality and chances to break White's center at some point with well timed ...f6. }
