1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 g6 { To keep our repertoire coherent. } 5.
Nf3 Bg7 6. dxc5 Qxc5 { Rare but tricky } 7. Na3 { should be met by } 7... Nf6
{ a6 8. Nc4 Nd7 9. a4 gave White little something in G.Pap - P. Nguyen, Graz 2016. Comparing to some other line where White has already commited his Bishop to e3 White has more options here. }
8. Be3 Qa5 9. Nc4 Qc7
{ Despite loosing one tempo Black can argue White's Knight is not so great on c4 as with the pawn still on a7 the b6 square is well covered. }
10. Qa4+ Bd7 11. Qa3
{ 11. Qa5 Qxa5   Qc8 !?  12. Nxa5 b6 was equal in B.Belyakov - A.Gupta, Doha 2014 }
11... Nc6
{ Nd5 12.O-O-O Nxe3 13. Nxe3 Bc6 14. Bb5 !! was super crazy in Y.Tong - S.Kudrin, Beijing 1998 }
12. Nb6 Rd8 13. Nxd7 Rxd7 14. Be2
{ According to Bangiev White is slightly better but I disagree. In this structure I don't think White's Bishops are better than Black's Knights and it is Black who has better control in the centre. }
14... Nd5 { White needs to be careful to keep the balance. } *

